oundly changed by digital developments. It contrasts different aspects of this temporality, bringing together experts from critical cartography, media studies and science and technology studies. Together the chapters offer a unique interdisciplinary focus revealing the complex and social ways in which time in wrapped up with digital technologies and revealed in everyday mapping tasks: from navigating across cities, to serving as scientific groundings for news stories; from managing smart cities, to visual art practice. It brings time back into the map!  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunication. Mass media. 0aElectronic data processing. 0aGeography (General). 0aInformation technology. 0aSocial sciences (General). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Geography.2bisacsh  aDigital mapping.  aTechnologies.  aTemporality.  aTime.1 aAbend, Pablo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDriesser, Tuur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGekker, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGekker, Alex, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGerlach, Joe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanchard, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHind, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHind, Sam, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLammes, Sybille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLammes, Sybille, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r